Here are both approaches for .NET MAUI Shell navigation:

**1. Passing a simple string ID**

```csharp
// ProductListPage.xaml.cs or ViewModel command
async void OnProductSelected(Product product)
{
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync($"{nameof(ProductDetailsPage)}?productId={product.Id}");
}
```

**2. Passing the full object**

```csharp
async void OnProductSelected(Product product)
{
    var navParams = new Dictionary<string, object>
    {
        { "product", product }
    };
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync(nameof(ProductDetailsPage), navParams);
}
```

> **Key difference:** simple types use the query-string overload; complex objects use the `IDictionary<string, object>` overload.

---

**Receiving both on the ViewModel with `IQueryAttributable`:**

```csharp
public class ProductDetailsViewModel : ObservableObject, IQueryAttributable
{
    private string _productId;
    private Product _product;

    public void ApplyQueryAttributes(IDictionary<string, object> query)
    {
        // Approach 1: string parameter arrives as string
        if (query.TryGetValue("productId", out var idObj))
        {
            _productId = idObj.ToString();
            // Load product from service using _productId
        }

        // Approach 2: full object arrives as-is
        if (query.TryGetValue("product", out var productObj) && productObj is Product p)
        {
            _product = p;
        }
    }
}
```

**Wire-up checklist:**

```csharp
// Register the route
Routing.RegisterRoute(nameof(ProductDetailsPage), typeof(ProductDetailsPage));

// Set the ViewModel as BindingContext (or use DI)
public ProductDetailsPage(ProductDetailsViewModel vm)
{
    InitializeComponent();
    BindingContext = vm;
}
```

**When to use which:**
- **String ID** — lightweight, survives deep-link URIs, good when you'll fetch fresh data anyway.
- **Full object** — avoids a redundant lookup, but only works for in-app navigation (not deep links).
